{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians --> | name = Ste McCabe | image = Ste McCabe.jpg | caption = Ste McCabe at the New Oxford, Salford, as part of the Sounds From The Other City Festival, 2011. | image_size = | background = group_or_band | birth_place = [[Liverpool]], England | genre = [[Independent music|Indie]], [[queercore]], [[Punk rock|punk]] | years_active = 2006–2014 | label = Cherryade Records | associated_acts = Stephen Nancy | website = {{URL|http://www.ste-mccabe.co.uk}}
}}
'''Ste McCabe''' (from [[Liverpool]], England) is an English DIY, [[queercore]] singer-songwriter, previously based in [[Manchester]], and later [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]].
==Career== McCabe started performing solo in 2006, using only a drum machine and electric guitar as an alternative to a full band. (Previous band Stephen Nancy had existed between 1999 and 2002.)<ref>http://megapeng.net/features/feature_08.12_ste.mccabe.html</ref> In 2008 he signed to Cherryade Records with whom he released his first official solo EP "Pink Bomb" as a limited-edition CD.<ref>[http://www.cherryademusic.co.uk/buypb.html "Cherryade Records website"]. Retrieved on November 25th, 2010.</ref> His first album, ''Hate Mail'' followed later that year and received favourable reviews from underground/alternative press and mainstream gay media such as ''[[Gay Times]]'', who described McCabe as "armed with a mean, lean, bedroom Disco drum machine, a cheap guitar and his biggest asset; a mind and a loud mouth to speak it."<ref>[http://www.gaytimes.co.uk/Magazine/InThisIssue-articleid-5041-sectionid-696.html "Gay Times, December 2008"]. Retrieved on November 29, 2010.</ref> Over the following year McCabe became known as an LGBT rights activist as well as a popular underground musician,<ref>[http://www.artrocker.tv/features/article/the-gospel-of-ste-mccabe "Ste McCabe interview for Artrocker Magazine"]. Retrieved on November 25, 2010.</ref> performing at events such as London Literature Festival at [[Royal Festival Hall]] and [[Indietracks]] Festival in Derbyshire. The same year he joined [[Dandelion Radio]] as a DJ, playing "leftist, feminist, [[queer]] positive" underground music.<ref>[http://www.dandelionradio.com/ste.htm "Ste McCabe's Dandelion Radio page"]. Retrieved on November 25, 2010.</ref>
McCabe's second album, ''Murder Music'', was released in 2009, and featured a duet with avante-garde performer [[David Hoyle (performance artist)|David Hoyle]]. He was subsequently featured in ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'', ''[[Gay Times]]'' and ''[[Artrocker]]'' magazine, which in September 2010 featured his open letter to [[The Pope]] protesting against [[Benedict XVI]]'s visit to the UK.<ref>[http://www.artrocker.tv/magazine/article/issue-104-october-2010 "Artrocker, Issue 104"]. Retrieved on November 29th, 2010.</ref> He has performed at LGBT rights festivals across Europe such as Noc Walpurgii in Warsaw, Poland and [[Gay Pride]] 2010 in Bristol, England.
Ste has received national UK radio play on stations such as BBC 6Music and BBC Radio 1.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/1917bfc9-697d-4595-accf-b2ed72d7c1ad "BBC Website"] Retrieved on December 9th, 2012.</ref> With the release of his 3rd album, ''Bad Kitty'', he toured Europe again in October and November 2012.
McCabe performed onstage with English leftist singer [[Billy Bragg]] at [[Glastonbury Festival]] in 2013<ref>[http://www.glastonburyfestivals.co.uk/areas/left-field "Glastonbury Festival Website"] Retrieved on July 5th, 2013.</ref> Latest album ''Brains of Britain'' was released in October 2014 and included a collaboration with Bragg.<ref>http://www.songwritingmagazine.co.uk/music-reviews/brains-of-britain-by-ste-mccabe-album/19030</ref> He promoted the album with a final tour of the USA.
