{{About||the 2017 Italian film|The Place (2017 film)}} {{Infobox military structure |name=The Place |image=Old Drill Hall, Duke's Road - geograph.org.uk - 777806.jpg |caption =The Place |type = Drill Hall |map_type = Greater London |pushpin_map_caption = Location within London |location = [[London Borough of Camden|Camden]], [[London]] |coordinates = {{Coord|51|31|38|N|0|7|43|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} |ownership = |operator = |built = 1888-1889 |used=1989-Present |architect = Robert Edis |built_for = [[War Office]] |garrison = |occupants = }} '''The Place''' is a [[dance]] and [[performance]] centre in Duke's Road near [[Euston railway station|Euston]] in the [[London Borough of Camden]]. It is the home of [[London Contemporary Dance School]], [[Richard Alston Dance Company]], and the Robin Howard Dance Theatre.
==History== The building was designed by Robert Edis as the headquarters of the [[Artists Rifles|20th Middlesex (Artists) Volunteer Rifle Corps]] and built by Charles Kynoch and Company of Clapham between 1888 and 1889.<ref name=blb>{{cite web|author=Good Stuff |url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-477148-the-place-and-attached-railings-17-camde |title=The Place and Attached Railings - Camden - Greater London - England |publisher=British Listed Buildings |date=1997-08-01 |accessdate=2016-12-14}}</ref> It was subsequently officially opened by the [[Edward VII|Prince of Wales]].<ref name=blb/> The 20th Middlesex (Artists) Volunteer Rifle Corps became the [[London Regiment|28th (County of London) Battalion, London Regiment (Artists Rifles)]] in 1908.<ref name=step>{{cite web|url=http://www.steppingforwardlondon.org/assets/docs/sections/17.pdf|title=Drill Hall Register: A list of the locations of London Drill Halls since 1908|publisher=|accessdate=14 May 2017}}</ref> The battalion was mobilised at the drill hall in August 1914 before being deployed to the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1914-1918.net/london.htm|title=The London Regiment|publisher=The Long, Long Trail|accessdate=21 May 2017}}</ref> When the London Regiment was broken up and the battalions reallocated to other units in August 1937, the hall became the home of the [[Rifle Brigade (The Prince Consort's Own)|Artists Rifles, The Rifle Brigade]].<ref>Gregory, p. 253</ref> The unit was disbanded in 1945, after the [[World War II|Second World War]], but reformed again in the Rifle Brigade in January 1947 but transferred to the [[Army Air Corps (United Kingdom)|Army Air Corps]] in July 1947 as the [[Special Air Service|21st Special Air Service Regiment (Artists Rifles)]].<ref>Gregory, p. 297</ref> The drill hall fell vacant when the 21st Special Air Service Regiment moved out to the [[Duke of York's Headquarters]] in the late 1960s.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SCio3hI8G7wC&pg=PT54&lpg=PT54&dq=%22Duke+of+York%27s+barracks%22+21st+Regiment+SAS&source=bl&ots=xRpJoqlOCq&sig=0EQsKgX1xE4SFDP4uZ1A03ZLXFY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi9o6T9tKHUAhUJBsAKHahnAxYQ6AEIIjAA#v=onepage&q=%22Duke%20of%20York's%20barracks%22%2021st%20Regiment%20SAS&f=false|title=Mad, Bad and Dangerous to Know|first=Ranulph |last=Fiennes|publisher=Hodder|year=2008|isbn=978-0340951699}}</ref>
The drill hall, which had been colloquially known as "The Artists Place", became simply "The Place" when the Contemporary Ballet Trust took over the premises in 1969.<ref name=history>{{cite web|url=http://www.theplace.org.uk/history-place|title=A History of The Place|publisher=The Place|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref> In 1976 the Contemporary Ballet Trust, under the leadership of [[Robin Howard]], acquired the freehold of the premises as well as a site in Flaxman Terrace so facilitating an extension studio block to be built.<ref name=history/> In the 1970s the Contemporary Ballet Trust established the [[London Contemporary Dance School]] and the [[London Contemporary Dance Theatre]] both of which were formed at The Place; in 1994 the latter body was succeeded by the [[Richard Alston Dance Company]] which remains located at The Place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lcds.ac.uk/|title=London Contemporary Dance School|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref> Then in 1999 a major redevelopment programme, principally funded by the [[National Lottery (United Kingdom)|National Lottery]], allowed the refurbishment of the original drill hall and the replacement of the studio block with six new state-of-the-art dance studios designed by architects [[Allies and Morrison]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/home/a-sense-of-place/184828.article|title=A Sense of Place|publisher=Architect's Journal|date=18 October 2001|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref> Two further dance studios, the Weston Studio and the Monument Studio, were added in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lcds.ac.uk/history-london-contemporary-dance-school|title=History of London Contemporary Dance School|publisher=The Place|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref>
From 2004 to 2013 [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] sponsored [[The Place Prize]], a large contemporary choreography competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2011/apr/10/place-prize-dance-luke-jennings|title=The Place prize – the final|date=10 April 2011|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref> In September 2007, [[Kenneth Tharp]] OBE took up the new position of Chief Executive of The Place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/news/newsstory.php/17159/tharp-appointed-chief-exec-of-the-place|title=Tharp appointed chief exec of The Place and Thiarai joins Theatre Writing Partnership|date=12 June 2007|publisher=Stage News|accessdate=3 June 2017|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611220929/http://www.thestage.co.uk/news/newsstory.php/17159/tharp-appointed-chief-exec-of-the-place|archivedate=11 June 2011|df=}}</ref> Tharp stepped down in November 2016 and was replaced, as interim chief executive, by Steven Browning. In summer 2017 Clare Connor was permanently appointed to the post. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theplace.org.uk/interim-chief-executive|title=Interim Chief Executive|publisher=The Place|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref>
